    <content>&lt;b&gt;Review of Finance&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper examines whether more bank presence in underserved areas can improve house- holds’ health. Leveraging a 2005 Reserve Bank of India policy and a regression discon- tinuity design, I demonstrate that five years post-policy, treatment districts have 27 more bank branches than control districts. This expansion increases household employment and access to savings accounts, enhancing health investments. On the healthcare supply side, hospitals utilize more credit and expand services. Six years after the policy, households in treatment districts are 19 percentage points less likely to suffer from non-chronic illnesses in a given month. Chronic diseases remain unaffected.</content>
